AIM: This is an automation document to push your github code to a virtual machine or EC2 instance. 

Description: When your application is running on a VM, you need to automate your CI/CD pipeline. When there is any event on github like push, your code should automatically be deployed on the server. Also you should be able to run custom commands in there to restart your server.

STEP 1:

# set up the VM for webhook (assuming you have an ubuntu system)
sudo apt update 
sudo apt-get install webhook

# install python
sudo apt install python3

STEP 2:

# login to your VM 

Write a bash script where you can define the steps to pull the code:

---

#!/bin/bash

# Reset and pull latest code from branch
git reset --hard
git pull origin <branch-name>

# Run your commands after pull (in this example its a rails application)
bundle install
RAILS_ENV=production bundle exec rails assets:precompile
sudo systemctl restart <server (nginx, apache2, etc)>
sudo monit restart all
sudo service sidekiq restart
sudo service sidekiq_cron restart
sudo service sidekiq_panna restart

---

STEP 3:

# login to your vm where your code needs to pushed

create a webhook.py file and paste this code:

---
from flask import Flask, request
import subprocess
import threading

app = Flask(__name__)

def deploy():
    try:
        subprocess.run(["git", "pull"], cwd="/<your code directory path>", check=True)
        subprocess.run(["<script file location created in step 2>"], check=True)
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"Deployment error: {e}")

@app.route("/webhook", methods=["POST"])
def webhook():
    if request.method == "POST":
        # Run the deploy function in a separate thread
        threading.Thread(target=deploy).start()
        return "Accepted", 200

if __name__ == "__main__":
    app.run(host="0.0.0.0", port=5000)
---

Note: keeping host at 0.0.0.0 is important to communicate with github webhook and mention the port where webhook will be listening at.

STEP 4:

# now we need to create the webhook server 

Navigate to /etc/systemd/system (ubuntu system) and create a file webhook.service
Paste the following code

---

[Unit]
Description=GitHub Webhook Listener
After=network.target

[Service]
User=anuj
Group=anuj
ExecStart=/usr/bin/python3 /<path to the webhook file we created in step 3>webhook.py
WorkingDirectory=<working directory path where your actual code is present>
Restart=always
Environment="PATH=/usr/bin"

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target

---

Restart the webhook service:
sudo systemctl restart webhook.service
sudo systemctl enable webhook.service
sudo systemctl status webhook.service

Note: If webhook service status don't say "active", you can debug the issue further by running 
"journalctl -u webhook.service -f"

